Picked the top actionable `Ready` engineering card, `Sync GitHub PR and CI status into the coding feedback loop`, and implemented it on `feature/workspace-core-github-pr-feedback-sync-2026-03-08-r2`. Because the main workspace tree was already dirty with unrelated changes, I used a clean linked worktree at `/tmp/workspace-core-github-pr-feedback-sync-20260308-2` off the same repo.

The core change is in [tools/coding_feedback_loop.py](/tmp/workspace-core-github-pr-feedback-sync-20260308-2/tools/coding_feedback_loop.py): it now detects GitHub remotes, queries PR/check metadata via `gh` when available, classifies check rollups as `success`/`failure`/`pending`/`missing`, and folds that into review decisions with a safe fallback to local test evidence when GitHub data is missing. I added fixture-driven coverage in [tests/test_coding_feedback_loop.py](/tmp/workspace-core-github-pr-feedback-sync-20260308-2/tests/test_coding_feedback_loop.py) plus three PR payload fixtures, and moved the card to `Review` with exact evidence in [departments/coding/kanban/workspace-core.md](/tmp/workspace-core-github-pr-feedback-sync-20260308-2/departments/coding/kanban/workspace-core.md).

Verification passed:
- `python3 -m unittest tests.test_coding_feedback_loop -v` => 5 passed
- `python3 -m py_compile tools/coding_feedback_loop.py` => passed

The commit is `fd3ac23` with message `feat(coding): sync github pr checks into feedback loop`. The push step did not complete because this environment cannot resolve GitHub: `git push -u origin feature/workspace-core-github-pr-feedback-sync-2026-03-08-r2` failed with `Could not resolve host: github.com`. The branch is otherwise clean and ready to push once network/DNS access is available.
