codex
The remaining “conflict” is a false positive from the audit implementation itself: it scans `merge-tree` text for phrases like `added in both`, and our branch now contains that literal string in source code. I’m switching conflict detection to `git merge-tree --write-tree` and adding a regression test so the branch can be classified correctly after push.
Plan update
A third issue surfaced during live verification: merge-conflict detection was false-positive because it scanned merge-tree text for marker strings that can appear in source code.
  ✓ Refactor coding_feedback_loop root/kanban discovery to be worktree-aware instead of hardcoded to the main workspace path
  ✓ Add regression coverage for default root discovery in tests.test_coding_feedback_loop
  ✓ Prefer origin/main over stale local main in branch classification and cover it with a regression test
  → Replace text-scanned merge-tree conflict detection with a write-tree merge check and add regression coverage
  • Run targeted verification, push feature branch to origin, and capture the resulting branch status
